"Lee H., Shum C.K., Tseng K.-H., Guo J.-Y., Kuo C.-Y.","Present-day lake level variation from envisat altimetry over the northeastern qinghai-tibetan plateau: Links with precipitation and temperature",2011,"Terrestrial, Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences","22","2",,"169","175",,,10.3319/TAO.2010.08.09.01(TibXS),"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79955506965&partnerID=40&md5=3cfe404752e6c5c9b23d8ee802009650","Division of Geodetic Science, School of Earth Sciences, Ohio State University, Columbus, OH, United States; Department of Geomatics, National Cheng-Kung University, Tainan, Taiwan","Lee, H., Division of Geodetic Science, School of Earth Sciences, Ohio State University, Columbus, OH, United States; Shum, C.K., Division of Geodetic Science, School of Earth Sciences, Ohio State University, Columbus, OH, United States; Tseng, K.-H., Division of Geodetic Science, School of Earth Sciences, Ohio State University, Columbus, OH, United States; Guo, J.-Y., Division of Geodetic Science, School of Earth Sciences, Ohio State University, Columbus, OH, United States; Kuo, C.-Y., Department of Geomatics, National Cheng-Kung University, Tainan, Taiwan","Lakes in permafrost regions are highly sensitive to changes in air temperature, snowmelt, and soil frost. In particular, the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau (QTP) is one of the most sensitive regions in the world influenced by global climate change. In this study, we use retracked Enivsat radar altimeter measurements to generate water level change time series over Lake Qinghai and Lake Ngoring in the northeastern QTP and examine their relationships with precipitation and temperature changes. The response of water levels in Lake Qinghai and Lake Ngoring is positive with regards to precipitation amount. There is a negative relationship between water level and temperature change. These findings further the idea that the arid and high-elevation lakes in the northeastern QTP are highly sensitive to climate variations. Water level increases in Lake Qinghai in winter may indicate inputs of subsurface water associated with freeze-thaw cycles in the seasonally frozen ground and the active layer.","Climate variations; Lake water level; Qinghai-Tibetan plateau","active layer; air temperature; altimetry; climate variation; Envisat-1; freeze-thaw cycle; frozen ground; lake water; precipitation (climatology); water level; China; Ngoring Lake; Qinghai; Qinghai Lake; Qinghai-Xizang Plateau",,,,,,"Bamber, J.L., Ice sheet altimeter processing scheme (1994) Int. J. Remote Sens., 15, pp. 925-938. , doi: 10.1080/01431 169408954125. [Link]; Berry, P.A.M., Garlick, J.D., Freeman, J.A., Mathers, E.L., Global inland water monitoring from multi-mission altimetry (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett., 32, pp. L16401. , doi: 10.1029/2005GL022814. [Link]; Birkett, C.M., The contribution of TOPEX/POSEIDON to the global monitoring of climatically sensitive lakes (1995) J. Geophys. Res., 100, pp. 25179-25204. , doi: 10.1029/95JC02125. [Link]; Birkett, C.M., Contribution of the TOPEX NASA radar altimeter to the global monitoring of large rivers and wetlands (1998) Water Resources Research, 34 (5), pp. 1223-1239; Birkett, C.M., Mertes, L.A.K., Dunne, T., Costa, M.H., Jasinski, M.J., Surface water dynamics in the Amazon Basin: Application of satellite radar altimetry (2002) J. Geophys. Res., 107, p. 8059. , doi: 10.1029/20 01JD000609. [Link]; Brown, G.S., The average impulse response of a rough surface and its applications (1977) IEEE Trans. Antennas Propag., 25, pp. 67-74. , doi: 10.1109/TAP. 1977.1141536. [Link]; Cherkauer, K.A., Bowling, L.C., Lettenmaier, D.P., Variable infiltration capacity cold land process model updates (2003) Global Planet. Change, 38, pp. 151-159. , doi: 10.1016/S0921-8181(03)00025-0. [Link]; Davis, C.H., A robust threshold retracking algorithm for measuring ice-sheet surface elevation change from satellite radar altimeters (1997) IEEE Transactions on Geoscience and Remote Sensing, 35 (4), pp. 974-979. 